nch-speaking Europeans. This book examines different aspects of the life and literary culture associated with this French-speaking society. It is the first study of the crusades to bring questions of language and culture so intimately into conversation. Taking an interdisciplinary approach to the study of the crusader settlements in the Levant, this book emphasizes hybridity and innovation, the movement of words and people across boundaries, seas and continents, and the negotiation of identity in a world tied partly to Europe but thoroughly embedded in the Mediterranean and Levantine context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCrusadesyFirst, 1096-1099. 0aCrusades. 0aFrench languagexHistory. 0aFrench languageyTo 1300. 0aFrench languagezMiddle EastxHistory. 0aFrenchzMiddle EastxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCrusader States.  aCrusades.  aMedieval Mediterranean.  aMedieval Studies.  aOld French.  aPostcolonial Theory.1 aBlumenfeld-Kosinski, Renate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaggero, Massimiliano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandyside, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLester, Anne E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinervini, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorreale, Laura K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorreale, Laura K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNicolaou-Konnari, Angel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Nicholas L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Nicholas L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a